    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4114616792" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4114616792" />
    <a title="John" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/20198594-john"><img alt="John" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4114616792?book_show_action=true">Jul 14, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="John" class="user" itemprop="url" name="John" href="/user/show/20198594-john">John</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4114616792" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer186014603435106061">Stephen Sears is a fantastic writer ,and his books are a informative and a pleasure to read. After the Union defeat at Bull Run (aka Manassas), President Lincoln appointed George McClellan to lead. McClellan was a good organizer and popular with his men. However, he was extremely cautious and always believed the Confederates had more men. On the Confederate side we see the first military draft, which was highly controversial. I like this quote that Sears provided: Private Jesse Reid of the 4th S</span>
  <span id="freeText186014603435106061" style="display:none">Stephen Sears is a fantastic writer ,and his books are a informative and a pleasure to read. After the Union defeat at Bull Run (aka Manassas), President Lincoln appointed George McClellan to lead. McClellan was a good organizer and popular with his men. However, he was extremely cautious and always believed the Confederates had more men. On the Confederate side we see the first military draft, which was highly controversial. I like this quote that Sears provided: Private Jesse Reid of the 4th South Carolina thought Congress was taking the law into its hands unjustly; if volunteers were kept on for two more years, he asked, what was to prevent the lawmakers from keeping them on for ten more years? With conscription, he warned, “all patriotism is dead, and the Confederacy will be dead sooner or later.”<br /><br />McClellan planned to attack Richmond from the Virginia Peninsula. After his men landed, they slowly made their way to Richmond. At the Battle of Yorktown, the first battle, many Union troops accused McClellan of letting the enemy escape. As Joe Hooker said, "The retreat of the rebels I fear will play the devil with McClellan.” <br /><br />Eventually the Federals could see Richmond. People were fleeing the city because they thought that was it. Joseph Johnston, leading what would be the Army of Northern Virginia, was wounded in battle and McClellan ironically expressed he was happy to see Johnston was out and Robert E. Lee was commanding. Lee did not have the reputation he later had at that time. He attacked aggressively and this forced McClellan to pull back and eventually retreat to Washington DC, even winning against Lee at Malvern Hill. This was a campaign the North should have won. I think Sears wrote so elegantly "While he correctly judged General McClellan to be defensive-minded, it did not occur to him that General McClellan would give up so easily: that after a single battle—which the Federals won—he would decide to abandon his campaign, cut his losses, and run for safety. Lee followed the more logical reasoning that on June 27 McClellan was making a major effort to defend his White House supply line. 'The principal part of the Federal Army was now on the north side of the Chickahominy' was how Lee put it in his official report of the day’s events." It is sad to see so much life wasted for nothing, but the information and writing of Sears provide a good read. It is also refreshing to read about other campaigns that are not Gettysburg nor Antietam because we see another part of the war. A great read by Mr. Sears. </span>
  <a data-text-id="186014603435106061" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review4114616792">
  <td colspan="2">
